      "category": "ux",
      "title": "extractJSON heuristic uses fragile string search for 'findings' key",
      "body": "`strings.Contains(objs[i], `\"findings\"`)` matches any occurrence of the literal bytes `\"findings\"` anywhere in the JSON text — including inside a string value (e.g., a finding body that says `see \"findings\" section`). This is unlikely today but is a latent footgun: a developer debugging a misparse won't suspect this heuristic because the comment says 'contains a findings key', implying structural checking.",
      "suggestion": "For a cheap structural check: unmarshal into `map[string]json.RawMessage` and test `_, ok := m[\"findings\"]`. This is only run on a small number of already-validated JSON blobs, so the cost is negligible, and it eliminates the false-positive risk entirely.",
      "confidence": 7
    },
    {
      "file": "rival/internal/review/parse.go",
      "line": 47,
      "severity": "low",
      "category": "ux",
      "title": "extractJSON silently falls back with no diagnostic signal",
      "body": "When no object contains `\"findings\"`, the function silently returns the last JSON object (line 57). This is a reasonable fallback, but callers (and developers debugging parsing failures) get zero signal that the heuristic missed — the returned object may unmarshal into a zero-value struct with no findings, which looks like a clean review. A log line or a second return value indicating 'fallback used' would surface the ambiguity.",
      "suggestion": "Return a second boolean (`fallback bool`) or log at debug level when the `\"findings\"` heuristic doesn't match any object. This lets callers decide whether to warn the user that the output may be a schema echo rather than a real review.",
