=== REVIEW FROM gemini (gemini-3.5-flash) [role: arch_security] ===

{
  "summary": "The review of rival/internal/review/parse.go revealed three significant issues: a state-tracking bug where quotes before braces cause parsing to fail completely, a quadratic complexity risk during invalid brace scanning, and a logic bug where schema placeholders from the prompt are returned as false findings if the model fails or returns findings-free output.",
  "findings": [
    {
      "file": "rival/internal/review/parse.go",
      "line": 67,
      "severity": "high",
      "category": "bug",
      "title": "State-tracking context loss in jsonObjects",
      "body": "The function jsonObjects starts scanning for matching braces from the index of the first '{' byte (remaining[start:]) rather than tracking the state from the beginning of the string. If there are any curly braces inside string literals or comments before the actual JSON payload (e.g., in the echoed user prompt, shell commands, or markdown explanations), the parser starts with inStr = false at the '{' and misinterprets the subsequent double-quotes and braces. This can cause it to completely fail to extract a valid JSON payload.",
      "suggestion": "Scan the string sequentially from index 0, maintaining string and escape state, and push/pop brace indexes from a stack to accurately match braces.",
      "confidence": 10
    },
    {
      "file": "rival/internal/review/parse.go",
      "line": 52,
      "severity": "high",
      "category": "architecture",
      "title": "Echoed prompt schema fallback hides missing/invalid LLM outputs",
      "body": "In extractJSON, the function loops backward over all found JSON objects to return the last one containing the 'findings' key, falling back to the last valid JSON object if none contain it. However, because the CLI prompt always includes the JSON output contract (which contains the 'findings' schema placeholder), the prompt itself is always parsed as a valid JSON object containing 'findings'. If the model's actual output is missing, malformed, or fails to include the 'findings' key, the loop will match the schema placeholder in the prompt instead of falling back to the last valid object. This results in the tool silently parsing and returning the mock findings from the prompt (e.g. path/to/file line 42) as real issues.",
      "suggestion": "Skip any extracted JSON objects that contain the schema placeholder file path ('path/to/file'), or ensure that we only search for findings within JSON objects generated after the prompt text.",
      "confidence": 10
    },
    {
      "file": "rival/internal/review/parse.go",
      "line": 118,
      "severity": "medium",
      "category": "performance",
      "title": "Quadratic parsing complexity in jsonObjects",
      "body": "In jsonObjects, if a candidate substring is invalid JSON, the code advances remaining by only one character (remaining = remaining[start+1:]) and rescans the remainder of the string. In the presence of many nested curly braces (e.g., in nested source code blocks or logs containing Go/C structures), this results in quadratic O(N^2) time complexity, leading to high CPU usage and potential denial of service.",
      "suggestion": "Use a single-pass scanner to parse and validate braces, advancing past the matched candidate block instead of backtracking and rescanning.",
      "confidence": 9
    }
  ]
}

=== END REVIEW ===

