  "summary": "The parser handles the intended happy path, but its JSON extraction still has correctness holes around echoed prompt/schema objects and noisy brace-heavy logs. The maintainability-only duplication finding is not worth blocking on.",
  "findings": [
    {
      "file": "rival/internal/review/parse.go",
      "line": 53,
      "severity": "high",
      "category": "bug",
      "title": "Echoed schema can be parsed as real review output",
      "body": "extractJSON searches every valid JSON object in the full CLI log and returns the last one containing \"findings\". If the CLI echoes the prompt's JSON output contract and the model emits no valid review payload afterward, the schema example with placeholder data such as path/to/file can be selected and unmarshaled as real findings instead of producing a parse failure.",
      "suggestion": "Ignore prompt/schema JSON explicitly, or only scan the answer region. Also validate candidate payloads structurally and reject known placeholder schema values before returning them.",
      "confidence": 10,
      "found_by": [
        "gemini"
      ]
    },
    {
      "file": "rival/internal/review/parse.go",
      "line": 67,
      "severity": "medium",
      "category": "bug",
      "title": "Stray brace before payload can prevent extraction",
      "body": "jsonObjects starts each candidate at the next '{' with inStr reset to false. A brace in earlier prose, code, or quoted text can be treated as a JSON start; if that candidate never balances under the reset string state, found stays negative and the loop breaks, so a later valid JSON payload is never considered.",
      "suggestion": "Use a single pass over the full string that maintains quote and escape state globally, or continue scanning for later candidate starts after an unbalanced non-JSON region instead of breaking.",
      "confidence": 9,
      "found_by": [
        "gemini"
      ]
    },
    {
      "file": "rival/internal/review/parse.go",
      "line": 118,
      "severity": "medium",
      "category": "performance",
      "title": "Invalid brace candidates can cause quadratic scanning",
      "body": "When a balanced candidate is not valid JSON, jsonObjects advances by one byte and rescans the remainder. Large logs or code blocks with many nested braces can make this repeatedly scan overlapping suffixes, producing O(N^2) behavior.",
      "suggestion": "Replace the retry-by-one-byte loop with a single-pass scanner that records balanced object ranges and validates each range once.",
      "confidence": 8,
      "found_by": [
        "gemini"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "recommendation": {
    "status": "request_changes",
    "summary": "Fix the extraction logic before approving; it can silently return prompt placeholders as findings or miss valid payloads in noisy output."
  }
}
